Room Link: https://tryhackme.com/room/containment

This room is different from most TryHackMe challenges. You’re not just running commands in a terminal — you’re working alongside an AI incident response assistant that has access to the same filesystem you do. The challenge is designed to show how AI can meaningfully accelerate a real DFIR investigation, while still requiring you to think like an analyst.

The scenario: you’re a Security Analyst at West Tech, a classified defence and R&D contractor. Senior researcher Oliver Deer’s workstation has been flagged for unusual network activity, a ransom note was found on the desktop, and sensitive project data appears to have been exfiltrated and encrypted. Your job is to investigate, recover the data, and neutralise the threat.
Setup

After the machines finish booting, you get access to two things:

1. SSH access to the compromised workstation:

ssh o.deer@<machine-ip>
# Password provided in the room

2. The AI IR assistant:

http://<machine-ip>:7860?__theme=light

The AI is deployed on the same system as the workstation, meaning you can pass it file paths directly in your prompts. It has specialised tools built in that it can invoke intelligently based on context — you don’t need to trigger them manually.

    Note: The AI takes a moment to wake up. The first prompt will be slower than subsequent ones — just be patient.

The Investigation
Step 1: Orient Yourself on the Workstation

After connecting via SSH, start by checking what’s present in the home directory:

o.deer@west-tech-workstation:~$ ls
Desktop    Downloads  Music     Public     Videos  qwen-output
Documents  Mail       Pictures  Templates  alarms  westtech_projects_encrypted.zip

Two things immediately stand out:

    westtech_projects_encrypted.zip — this is almost certainly the exfiltrated and encrypted data
    qwen-output/ — a directory that will become relevant shortly

Step 2 : Hunt the Outlier PCAP

The hint tells you the attacker made a mistake: they accidentally exfiltrated their own working notes, and the fragments are buried in a PCAP file. That PCAP contains the password to the encrypted archive.
